Rating: 3
In my opinion, this recipe is flawed, but fixable (and worth fixing) The first time I made it, I used a food processor to grate the dough - and it did so very quickly, so that the dough was in the form of frozen flakes when I put it into the 9 x 13 pan. As a result, after 40 minutes, the dough in the middle of the pan was not as completely cooked as I would have liked, even tho the top browned well. I also felt that 1 cup of raspberry jam was too assertive, and overpowered the buttery flavor of the shortbread. The second time, I used a manual grater (which was tough on knuckles and arms, but worked well. The dough was more defrosted, and cooked up better. I also cut the raspberry jam down to 1/2 cup - and I prefer the result. In the future, I may go back to the food processor dough grating technique, but I will now know to leave the dough in the pan at room temp. for about 15 mins. after grating to allow it to defrost somewhat before I bake it.

Rating: 4
These cookies are just delicious! My teenagers beg for me to make them. Everyone I have served them to wants the recipe. We have decided we like a bit more jam in the center, and other flavors besides raspberry are equally yummy. Also, I cut them smaller-they are so rich! These cookies freeze well, just sprinkle on the powdered sugar after thawing and just before serving.